    	<annotation>
    		
            	<!-- Marginalia -->
    		
        		<marginalia hand="Italian">
        			<language ident="LA">
            				<position place="head" book_orientation="0">
                    				<marginalia_text>
                    					Diogeni nemo vir, nisi Diogenes.
                      				</marginalia_text>
            					<person name="Diogenes of Sinope"/>
	            				<emphasis method="chalk" type="straight"/>
	            			</position>
        			</language>
        			<translation>
        				To Diogenes, no one is a man, except Diogenes.
        			</translation>
        		</marginalia>
    		<marginalia hand="Italian">
    			<language ident="LA">
    				<position place="intext" book_orientation="0">
    					<marginalia_text>
    						Philosophus, Philautus.
    					</marginalia_text>
    					<person name="Philautus"/>    					
    				</position>
    			</language>
    			<translation>
    				A philosopher, Philautus.
    			</translation>
    		</marginalia>
    		<marginalia hand="Italian">
    			<language ident="LA">
    				<position place="tail" book_orientation="0">
    					<marginalia_text>
    						Cert&egrave; ingens vir, Si tam fuisset agendi
    						potens, qu&agrave;m patiendi inuictus. Unde no[n] magis
    						summoru[m] Regu[m], qua[m] Diogenis stilus; Inuictissimus.
    					</marginalia_text>
    					<person name="Diogenes of Sinope"/>
    					<emphasis method="chalk" type="straight"/>
    				</position>
    			</language>
    			<translation>
    				A man is certainly great, if he is as strong in action, as he is unconquerable in enduring.
    				Whence, the pen of Diogenes, rather than that of the greatest kings, is the most unconquerable.
    			</translation>
    		</marginalia>
        
    		<marginalia hand="Italian" marginalia_id="Ha2.032v_0001" marginalia_continues_from="Ha2.033r_0001" marginalia_from_transcription="Ha2.033r.xml" book_id="FolgersHa2">
    			<language ident="LA">
    				<position place="right_margin" book_orientation="270">
    					<marginalia_text>
    						<!-- Continued from facing page, left margin, Ha2.033r. -->
    						|| cedit vlli. Vir est, qui Omnes, et Neminem contemnit: solum curat Seipsum.
    					</marginalia_text>
    					<emphasis method="chalk" type="straight"/>
    				</position>
    				<position place="intext" book_orientation="270">
    					<marginalia_text>
    						vt Diogenes solum respiciens Diogenem, +
    					</marginalia_text>
    					<person name="Diogenes of Sinope"/>
    				</position>
    				<position place="left_margin" book_orientation="270">
    					<marginalia_text> 
    						+ spernebat Aristotelem philosophu[m]: Platonem legislatore[m]: Demosthenem Oratore[m]: Demade[m]
    						pragmaticu[m]: Philippu[m] Rege[m]: ipsu[m] orbis Victorem Alexandru[m]. Sibi ipse Soli addictus,
    						neminem animo venerabatur Diogenes pra[e]ter Diogenem. Vnicus sua a[e]stimatione vir.
    					</marginalia_text>
    					<person name="Aristotle"/>
    					<person name="Plato"/>
    					<person name="Demosthenes"/>
    					<person name="Demades"/>
    					<person name="Philip II of Macedon"/>
    					<person name="Alexander the Great"/>
    				</position>
    			</language>
    			<translation>
    				as Diogenes regarded Diogenes alone, he spurned Aristotle the philosopher, Plato the legislator, Demosthenes the orator, 
    				Demades the pragmatist, Philip the King, even Alexander, conqueror of the world. Devoted to himself alone, Diogenes revered
    				no one in his heart except Diogenes. In his estimation, a unique man.
    			</translation>
    		</marginalia>
        
